<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   SEOUL, South Korea -- South Korea reported its highest
monthly inflation rate and widest monthly trade deficit in
nine years.
   Consumer prices rose 1.9% in May from the previous month,
the largest monthly gain since June 1981, according to the
Economic Planning Board. In addition, the nation registered a
trade deficit of $810 million in May, the widest since
December 1981, when the trade balance showed a gap of $894
million, according to the Ministry of Trade and Industry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Economic Planning Board also reported that wholesale
prices rose by 1.1% in May from the previous month.
   As a result of the monthly gain, consumer prices surged
6.7% during the first five months of this year, exceeding
last year's inflation rate of 5.7% and this year's yearly
target of 5% to 7%.
   Wholesale prices rose 3.1% during the first five months.
   The Ministry of Trade and Industry said exports in May
rose 5.6% from a year earlier to $5.22 billion, while imports
surged 20% to $6.03 billion, leaving a deficit of $810
million, on a customs clearance basis.
   As a result, the trade balance during the first five
months of this year showed a gap of $3.1 billion, exceeding
government projections of $2 billion for the year.
